This comprehensive project will take co2 data from the south pole, and we will try and fit model(s) that account for the auto correlation (correlation of variables throughout time) and use it to predict 3 years into the future.

We will fit multiple seperate models and compare them purely based off their ability to predict (MSE / MAD).

We will plot and decompose the csp data to get an idea of the relationships between the components.

plot(csp.ts,type='l')

Looking at the observed data, we can see that there is an upward trend, where the amplitude of seasonality doesn’t vary with the height of the trend. This looks like an additive relationship. So we definitely have seaonality, and there is a trend.

plot(decompose(csp.ts))

Looking at the random data, it seems like our randomness is also constant over, and with this, we will not have to transform the data.

The plan out of the gate is to look at a: Linear model (GLS) Seas(Harmonic) w/ ARIMA for Autocorrs. Linear model (GLS) Seas(Indicator) w/ ARIMA for Autocorrs. Holt Winters SARIMA

Finally, we will use a test / train split to compare our overall performance of our models.

So first, lets split our data. The training set has the first 26 years while the test set will contain the last 3 that we will compare our models with.

csp.tr = window(csp.ts,end=c(2013,12))
csp.test = window(csp.ts,st=c(2014,1))

FITTING MODELS: LINEAR REGRESSIVE INDICATOR/FACTOR MODEL

We will start off by standardizing TIME and getting the Seasonal factors

TIME = 1:length(csp.tr)
Seas = cycle(csp.tr)

Looking at the decomposed trend, we can see that it is fairly linear. But I will add up to TIME^4 for predictors.

csp.tr.ind = lm(csp.tr~0+TIME+I(TIME^2)+I(TIME^3)+I(TIME^4)+factor(Seas))

TIME^2 is significant when TIME^3 is removed

csp.tr.ind = lm(csp.tr~0+TIME+I(TIME^2)+factor(Seas))

We will look at the residuals to see if there is any remaining structure

acf(csp.tr.ind$residuals)

As we can see, there are still a ton of significant lags / autocorrelation

We will have to fit an arima model the residuals of the linear indicator model.

We can let the auto.arima function do the hard work, and fit a best fit Arima model to the residuals

csp.tr.ind.am = auto.arima(csp.tr.ind$residuals)
csp.tr.ind.am

Lets look at our acf of the residuals of this model now

acf(csp.tr.ind.am$residuals)

This correlogram looks great, and the ARIMA model was able to explain the rest of the autocorrelations!

We do not really care about AIC at all as we cannot combine the AIC of these two models without more experience, we will just go with this correlogram.

One model down, many more to go.

FITTING MODELS: LINEAR REGRESSIVE HARMONIC/SINUSODAL MODEL

We will generate 12 total sinusodal vectors / 2 matrecies for our harmoic seasons.

SIN = COS = matrix(nrow=length(time(csp.tr)),ncol=6)
for(i in 1:6){
  COS[,i]=cos(2*pi*i*time(csp.tr))
  SIN[,i]=sin(2*pi*i*time(csp.tr))
}

We will once again, standardize time based on the csp training time series

TIME = (time(csp.tr)-mean(time(csp.tr)))/sd(time(csp.tr))

Now to compare both linear models fairly, I will start with the same predictors, but may use stepwise for this model.

csp.tr.har1 = lm(csp.tr~TIME+I(TIME^2)+I(TIME^3)+I(TIME^4)+
                  COS[,1]+SIN[,1]+
                  COS[,2]+SIN[,2]+
                  COS[,3]+SIN[,3]+
                  COS[,4]+SIN[,4]+
                  COS[,5]+SIN[,5]+
                  COS[,6]+SIN[,6])

TESTING MODELS’ PREDICTION PERFORMANCE

Now we want to test the models on the test time series set that we set aside in the beginning. We will use the MAD and MSE to compare models with each other.

MAD ~ Mean Absolute Differences MSE ~ Mean Square Error

MAD First

# Factor LM
ind.MAD = mean(abs(csp.test-csp.tr.ind.pred))
# Harmonic with power predictors
har.lm.MAD = mean(abs(csp.test-csp.tr.har.pred_lm))
# Harmonic corrected
har.corrected.MAD = mean(abs(csp.test-csp.tr.har.pred_corrected))
# Holt Winters
hw.MAD = mean(abs(csp.test-csp.tr.hw.pred))
# SARIMA model
am.MAD = mean(abs(csp.test-csp.tr.am.pred$pred))

measures = data.frame(MAD = c(ind.MAD,har.lm.MAD,
                              har.corrected.MAD,hw.MAD,am.MAD))

Now which model do I choose…

It seemed like using a GLS was the right move because both the Indicator and corrected harmonic models -which used gls to correct- have very low MAD and MSE Score unlike the uncorrected Harmonic model Har_L

The Linear Regressive Indicator Model seems to perform the best in both metrics, so lets now Refit the Indicator Linear model to the full dataset and predict forward 3 years.
